<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1896-01-26T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1896-01-26T00:00:00-05:00" n="457" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d457">
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Olney</persName> to Mr.
                                    <persName type="to">Dupuy de Lôme</persName>.</hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of state</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1896-01-26"><hi rend="italic">January 26,
                                1896</hi></date>.</dateline></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have yours of this date and have sent a
                            copy to the Secretary of the Treasury, Secretary of the Navy, and the
                            Attorney-General, expressing the hope that any attempted violation of
                            the international obligations of the United States would be
                            prevented.</p>
                        <p>I have also said that you would furnish each of them with the evidence,
                            or sources of evidence, justifying the statement contained in your
                            letter.</p>
                        <p>Begging you to accept the assurances of my highest consideration,</p>
                        <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Richard Olney.</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                </body></text></TEI>